column168: THE N&M TRANSFER DRIVER CALLED THE SAFETY OFFICE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:50 P.M. HE REPORTED THAT LIQUID MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE PORTABLE TANK HE HAD PICKED UP IN NEENAH.  HE WAS CALLING FROM THE CONSIGNEE'S DOCK IN GREEN BAY TO INFORM US THAT THEY WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE SHIPMENT.  OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO BRING THE RUPTURED PORTABLE TANK BACK TO THE N&M TRANSFER TERMINAL IN NEENAH.  WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED HE HAD LOST APPROXIMATELY 5-10 GALLONS OF THE ADHESIVE MATERIAL IN HIS TRAILER.  THE N&M TRANSFER SAFETY OFFICE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET PRIOR TO CLEANING THE TRAILER.  I ALSO CONTACTED A MANUFACTIRER OF CARDBOARD PORTABLE TANKS SIMILAR TO THIS ONE, REQUESTING INFORMATION ON HOW TO STOP THE LEAK.  THEY WERE UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY INFORMATION THAT WAS USEFUL. OUR DOCK SUPERVISORS VERIFIED THE FACT THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE OUTSIDE OF THE VALVE AREA, WHERE THE PLASTIC LINER IS SEALED TO THE HARD PLASTIC VALVE.  I BELIEVE THERE ARE TWO POSSIBILITIES REGARDING THE CAUSE OF THEIS SPILL 1. THE SEAL AROUND THE PLASTIC VALVE BROKE LOOSE, CAUSING THE RUPTURE. 2. THE TOWMOTOR OPERATOR (AT WSI NEENAH) SOMEHOW HIT THE VALVE OF THE TANK AGAINST THE FRONT WALL OF THE TRAILER, CAUSING A TEAR IN THE PLASTIC LINER THAT CONNECTS TO THE VALVE. WE WERE UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AT OUR NEENAH FACILITY, SO WE ALLOWED ALL 300 GALLONS TO DRAIN IN TO SALVAGE DRUMS.  IT IS OUR RECOMMENDATION THAT STRONGER PERFORMANCE STANDARDS BE INTROUDUCED REGARDING CARDBOARD PORTABLE TANKS.  I ALSO SUGGEST THAT SHIPPERS SHOULD NOT BE ALLOWED TO SHIP THESE TYPES OF TANKS WITH VALVES PRE-INSERTED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  VALVES SHOULD BE INSERTED BY THE CONSIGNEE AFTER THEY ARRIVE AT DESTINATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS INITIATING PRODUCT FLOW INTO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK FROM A REMOTE FILL.  THE DRIVER HAD FOUND THE FILL WELL CONTAINED MELT DOWN AND HAD ENGAGED THE PLUNGER TO FREE THE TRAP AND CONDUCT HIS FITTING, THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY RESEAT THE PLUNGER AFTER DRAINING THE WELL. THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO BACK INTO THE WELL WHILE THE TANK WAS BEING FILLED.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THE PRODUCT SPILL OVER THE TRAP AND SPREAD ON THE CONCRETE PAD AND ADJACENT ASPHALT.  HE STOPPED THE PRODUCT FLOW INTO THE TANK AND USING THE MATERIALS CONTAINED IN HIS SPILL KIT, CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE.  HE THEN REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND HIS ACTIONS TO HIS SUPERVISON AND THE CITY OF BOSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE INCIDENT WAS ALSO IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO THE MASS. DEP.  THE DIRVER WAS COUNSELED ON HOW THE INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED.  THE CIRCUMSTANCES OF THE EVENT WILL BE REVIEWED WITH ALL DRIVERS AT THE NEXT MONTHLY SAFETY MEETING TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE.

ON 3-9-94, OUR DRIVER CONTACTED THE RESPONSIBLE PERSON AT SCHLEGEL TO UNLOAD A TRANSPORT OF APPROXIMATELY 4000 GALLONS OF TOLUOL.  OUR DRIVER ASKED THE RESPONSIBLE PERSON IF THE STORAGE TANK WAS ABLE TO HOLD ALL 4000 GALLONS.  THE PERSON RESPONDED YES.  WHILE DRAINING THE LAST COMPARTMENT OF PRODUCT, HE NOTICED THAT PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT OF THE OVERFLOW VALVE OF THE STORAGE TANK.  AT THIS TIME OUR DRIVER SHUT THE VALVE AND PUMP OFF. USING A CLAY-BASED FLOOR DRY, OUR DRIVER AND THE RESPONSIBLE PERSON FROM SCHLEGEL CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER WAS CONTACTED AND INSPECTED THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL.  SCHLEGEL WILL BE REPLACING THE FAULTY GUAGE WITH A NEW ONE.  WITH A NEW TANK SITE GUAGE INSTALLED, THIS WILL ALLOW FOR A MORE ACCURATE LEVEL DETERMINATION.

A LINE HAUL SHIPMENT OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, N.O.S., OPERATING UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF DOT E-8308, CONTAINING ONE HUNDRED AND THREE PACKAGES INCLUDING MO-99 GENERATORS OVERTURNED ON ROUTE 380 WEST IN TOBYHANNA, PA. THE CARGO VAN CONTAINED 73.4 T.I. ON MARCH 6, 1994, A FREAK SNOWSTORM CAUSING "WHITEOUT" CONDITIONS ON THE ROAD WITH SUBSEQUENT ICING AT THE MOUNTAINTOP LOCATION. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE INITIATED THE DEL-MED, INC. EMERGENCY PLAN BY NOTIFICATION OF HIS DISPATCHER USING THE CELLULAR PHONE OF A PASSING VEHICLE. INITIAL RESPONDENTS AT THE SITE WERE THE PA STATE POLICE FROM SWIFTWATER TROOP "S", A DEL-MED, INC. SUPERVISOR AND THE MONROE COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES BUREAU OF RADIATION PROTECTION (PA DER/BRP) WAS ALSO ALERTED TO THE SCENE. THE ROAD WAS CLOSED AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 THAT EVENING BY THE STATE POLICE ALTHOUGH IT IS STILL NOT CLEAR WHETHER THIS WAS DONE AS A RESULT OF INVOLVEMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OR FROM GENERALLY IMPASSABLE ROAD CONDITIONS. INITIAL ASSESSMENT OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE BY THE MONROE COUNTY RESPONDERS WAS THAT NONE OF THE FREIGHT  HAD LEFT THE VEHICLE. THIS GROUP ALLOWED THE RIGHTING OF THE VEHICLE AND ITS SUBSEQUENT TOWING TO THE NEARBY OFF RAMP. THE HIGHWAY WAS REOPENED BY THE PA STATE POLICE AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 HOURS. THE ARRIVAL OF THE DEL-MED SUPERVISOR ALLOWED A COMMUNICATIONS LINK WITH THE SCENE VIA HIS CELLULAR PHONE. THE SUPERVISOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE PRIOR TO THE AMBULANCE AND THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE PA DER/BRP. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE STATED TO HIS SUPERVISOR THAT HE DID NOT BELEIVE HE HAD BEEN INJURED IN THE MISHAP, HOWEVER HE WAS TAKEN TO THE NEAREST HOSPITAL EQUIPPED FOR RADIATION ACCIDENTS AFTER TURNING OVER CUSTODY OF THE SHIPMENT TO HIS SUPERVISOR. THE DISARRAYED CONFIGURATION OF THE FREIGHT AT THE TIME OF ARRIVAL OF THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE PA DER/BRP (MR. BOB LEWIS) DID NOT PRESENT REASON TO BELIEVE THAT ANY RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE PACKAGES. THE INITIAL EXPOSURE RATE MEASURED BY LEWIS ON THE FREIGHT ACCESSIBLE FROM THE SMALL BROKEN WINDOW IN THE REAR DOOR OF THE CARGO VAN WAS BETWEEN 400 AND 500 MR/HR. THE DEL-MED, INC. RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER WAS CONSULTED ON THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THIS READING USING THE CELLULAR PHONE LINK PRIOR TO THE OPENING OF THE VAN DOORS. THE DEL-MED, INC. RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER ADVISED MR. LEWIS THAT SUCH A RADIATION LEVEL WAS NOT UNEXPECTED IF THE PACKAGES WERE IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO ONE ANOTHER. SUCH MEASUREMENTS HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN RECORDED IN THE ASSESSMENT OF EXPOSURE RATES IN THE DEL-MED, INC. WAREHOUSE ON PALETTED GENERATORS. A PLAN TO TRANSFER THE PACKAGES FROM THE DAMAGED VEHICLE INTO THE BACK-UP VEHICLE WAS IMPLEMENTED. MR. LEWIS WAS ADVISED TO OBSERVED EACH PACKAGE FOR SIGNS OF SEVERE DAMAGE PENETRATING BEYOND THE OUTER LAYERS OF THE PACKAGING. SPECIAL ATTENTION WAS TO BE GIVEN TO ANY SEVERELY DAMAGED PACKAGES INCLUDING PRECAUTIONS FOR CONTAMINATION CONTROL. DUR

column168: ON 030594 AT APPROXIMATELY 7AM, REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO JENKS THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING AT SETTEGAST YARD. A CAR INSPECTOR SMELLED AN ODOR THEN SAW A VAPOR CLOUD AT THE TOP. REEDER ARRIVED AND OBSERVED THE CAR USING A TV CAMERA IN THE YARD OFFICE. THE VAPORS WERE VISIBLE COMING FROM THE TOP. REEDER NOTIFIED THE HOUSTON HAZ MAT TEAM TO ASSIST IN THE RESPONSE. USING LEVEL A PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARTUS, THE ENTRY TEAM DISCOVERED THE CAR LEAKING BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND NOZZLE. THE TEAM WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE 24 NUTS THAT SECURE THE PLATE AND STOP THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS RINSED USING A BASIC SOLUTION. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO A DU PONT IN LA PORTE, TX FOR UNLOADING. SEAL DUP 97681 WAS REMOVED BY REEDER. THE CAR WAS RESEALED WITH DALLAS 001264.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: APPROXIMATELY NOON ON FRIDAY 11, 1994 SPENCER COUNTIES PETROLEUM TRUCK WAS FORCED OFF THE ROAD. THE DRIVER OVER REACTED AND CAUSED THE TRUCK TO LEAVE THE ROAD. UPON LEAVING THE ROAD THE TRUCK TRAVEL A SHORT DISTANCE IN DENNIS FUEGER CORN FIELD. WHILE TRAVELING ALONG PARALLEL TO ROAD THE TRUCK FRONT BUMPER DUG INTO THE ROAD BANK CAUSING THE REAR OF THE TRUCK TO SWING SOUTH INITIATING THE ROLE OVER. THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER TWO AND A HALF TIMES. THE COVERS ON THE TANK STAYED IN TACK. ONE COVER WAS DRIPPING. IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK A VENT PIPE BROKE CAUSING AND ADDITIONAL LEAK. THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED WAS DIESEL FUEL. AT THE SIGHT, THERE WAS NO ROAD DITCH. THE TRUCK RAN OFF THE ROAD AT A POINT WHERE THE ROAD WAS UP HILL FROM WHERE THE TRUCK ENDED. THERE WAS A SLIGHT SLOPE TO THE SOUTH. UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE ACCIDENT THE FIRST EMPLOYEES AT THE SCENE DUG A SMALL DIKE DOWN SLOPE FROM THE FUEL TRUCK. BUCKETS AND ABSORBENT PADS WERE PUT TO USE ALMOST IMMEDIATELY TO CONTROL OR STOP THE LEAKS. APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR AND FIFTEEN MINUTES OUR COMPANIES HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRAILER ARRIVE WITH EQUIPMENT AND SPHAGSORB. THIS PRODUCT WILL ONLY ABSORB HYDROCARBONS AND NOT WATER. THIS PRODUCT WAS THEN APPLIED TO THE FUEL ON THE GROUND. ON THIS DAY THE SURFACE WATER WAS EXTREMELY HIGH AND ON THE SURFACE. THIS PREVENTED THE FUEL FROM GOING INTO THE SOIL AND THIS FACT MADE CLEAN UP RELATIVELY EASY. THE SPHAGSORB WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILLED PRODUCT WHEN AN AREA BECAME SOAKED MORE WAS APPLIED UNTIL THE ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED. THE WRECKER PEOPLE (DALLAS TOWING) ARRIVED AND COMMENCED TO RIGHT THE TRUCK. AFTER THE TRUCK WAS RIGHTED AND MOVE BACK ON TO HARD SURFACE THE REST OF THE FUEL IN THE TRUCK WAS PUMPED OFF SHOWING A LOSS OF ABOUT 75 GALLONS. APPROXIMATELY THIRTY OF THESE GALLONS WAS CAUGHT IN FIVE GALLON BUCKETS AND DID NOT REACHED THE SOIL. A BACKHOE OPERATOR JIM TULLEY WAS THEN CALLED AND THE SOIL CLEANUP WAS STARTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES OF SOIL WAS REMOVED OVER 2700 SQUARE FEET. WE REMOVED THIS AMOUNT TO ENSURE THAT WE HAD ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL. THE ACTUAL SPILL ONLY COVERED APPROXIMATELY 900 SQUARE FEET. AT THIS POINT THE SOIL WAS TAKEN TO SPENCER COUNTY FARM BUREAU COOP PLANT SIGHT, IN CHRISNEY INDIANA. THE SOIL WAS THEN STORED ON PLASTIC AND COVER WITH PLASTIC WITH A SMALL BERM AROUND THE PILE. REPORTING: THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CALLED AROUND NOON AND THE INCIDENT NUMBER IS 229498. IDEM WAS CALLED HOWEVER THE LOCAL SHERIFF HAD ALREADY REPORT THE SPILL. I TALKED TO MARK MAULK ABOUT THE SPILL AND RELATED THE FACTS AS I KNEW THEM AT THE TIME AROUND NOON SPENCER COUNTY TIME. MARK ASK THAT I CALL LATER IN THE DAY AND REPORT ON THE DISPOSITION OF THE SPILL. I RETURN THE CALL WITH CHRIS ROGERS PRESENT AT 4:15 AND I TALKED TO PAULA EGNER. MARK WAS NOT AVAILABLE AND I LEFT THE MESSAGE WITH PAULA AND ASKED THAT IF THERE WAS FURTHER CLARIFICATION PLEASE CALL MY CAR PHONE AT THE SPILL SIGHT. I ALSO REPORTED THE ACCIDENT TO DOT I TALKED TO FED B

THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A DELIVERY COURIER'S MORNING ROUTE WHEN THE COURIER NOTICED FUMES COMING FROM THE PACKAGE LOAD IN THE BACK OF THE VEHICLE.  AS THESE FUMES BECAME MORE PUGENT THE LONGER SHE WAS INTO HER DELIVERY CYCLE SHE BECAME CONCERNED AND PULLED HER VEHICLE OVER TO INVESTIGATE.  SHE INSPECTED HER LOAD AND NOTICED A PUDDLE OF LIQUID AROUND ONE OF THE PACKAGES.  THIS IS WHERE THE FUMES WERE COMING FROM AND AS SHE WAS IN THE VECINITY OF THE DELIVERY SHE WAS ADVISED TO ATTEMPT DELIVERY ON THE PACKAGE TO GET IT OFF THE VEHICLE AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE.  UPON DELIVERY SHE WAS INFORMED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS AN AIRCRAFT PART THAT HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY DRAINED OF FUEL.  SHE RETURNED TO THE STATION TO ADVISE FEDEX CORPORATE DG ON WHAT HAD OCCURED AND WHAT ACTION SHOULD BE TAKEN NEXT.  AS THE RECIPIENT WAS VERY CONCERNED ABOUT THE SAFETY ISSUES IN THIS MATTER THE RECIPIENT RELEASED THE OUTER PACKAGE THAT THE PART WAS SHIPPED IN BACK INTO FEDEX CUSTODY.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPERS DECLARATIONS ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE F.A.A. IS BEING CONTACTED FOR INVESTIGATION.

AFTER LOOKING THROUGH THE DRIVERS PAPERS I NOTICED THAT HE HAD A FLAMMABLE LIQUID ON BOARD.  KIM MARVIN WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  AFTER DETERMINING IT WAS SAFE FOR UNLOADING AND CLEANING UP, WE STRIPPED THE TRAILER TO FIND THE LEAKING BARREL.  THE DRIVER WAS TOLD TO LEAVE THE SHIPMENT BEHIND AND GO ON HIS WAY TO STOCKTON. AN IM PORTABLE TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM SCHERING PLOUGH CORPORATION LOCATED AT STATE ROAD 686 IN MANATI, PR TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, LOCATED AT RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP FLANGE ON THE TANK ONTO THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER AND THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOLTS HOLDING THE FLANGE IN PLACE WERE "HAND TIGHT" ALLOWING MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE FLANGE. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND SECURED THE FLANGE. ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE TANK CLOSURES WERE VISIBLE INSPECTED BUT WERE NOT PHYSICALLY CHECKED TO MAKE SURE ALL OF THE BOLTS WERE TIGHT. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PRE-TRIP PROCEDURES AND INSPECTIONS THAT MUST BE  TAKEN PRIOR TO MOVING ANY VEHICLE TO INSURE THAT ALL MANWAYS AND FLANGES ARE SECURE.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM THOMAS & BETTS CORP. LOCATED 3435 CHIP DRIVE IN ROANOKE, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT REST AREA LOCATED ON ROUTE 91 NORTH IN CONNECTICUT THE DRIVER NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED A FIELD SERVICE CREW FROM CLEAN HARBORS' NEW BRITIAN CONNECTICUT SERVICE CENTER. UPON ARRIVAL, THE FIELD SERVICE CREW ENTERED THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK ON THE TOP OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE CREW IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT  A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO ELECTRONIC SUPPORT SYSTEMS, INC. LOCATED AT 475 INDUSTRIAL DRIVE IN WEST CHICAGO, IL IN ORDER TO PICK UP A LOAD OF WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. (SULFURIC ACID/HYDROCHLORIC ACID MIXTURE). UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOADING FACILITY, THE DRIVER INITIATED THE LOADING PROCEDURES AND AS THE TANK WAS CLOSE TO  MAXIMUM CAPACITY, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE PUMPING ACTION CREATED A LAYER OF FOAM THAT PASSED THROUGH THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SHUTOFFS AND WAS RELEASE THROUGH THE PUMP MECHANISM. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE OPERATION, ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND CONTAINERIZED THE SPILL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS. THIS DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SHIPPER'S STORAGE AREA PENDING OFF-SIDE DISPOSAL. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO REDUCE THE VACUUM PRESSURE ON THE PUMPING SYSTEM WHEN LOADING MATERIALS THAT HAVE THE POTENTIAL TO FOAM IN ORDER TO PREVENT FOAM FROM FORMING.

A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO STABLEX CANADA LOCATED AT 760 BOUL. INDUSTRIAL IN BLAINEVILLE, QUEBEC. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO FREE LIQUID WAS OBSERVED. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A ROUTINE LOAD INSPECTION AND DISCOVERED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER. HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED A CONTAINMENT PAIL UNDER THE LEAK AND CALLED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED A CREW FROM CLEAN HARBORS' DEPTFORD, NJ SERVICE CENTER. UPON ARRIVAL, THE FILED SERVICE CREW INSPECTED CONTAINER AND DECIDED TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS TO A SECOND CONTAINER TO ENSURE THAT THE FREE LIQUID DISCOVERED IN THE CONTAINER COULD BE SOLIDIFIED. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE LIQUID MONTENT THAT WAS FOUND RESULTED FROM THE THAWING OF THE MATERIAL AS THE SHIPMENT WAS ENROUTE. IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE REAR DOOR SEAL FAILED ALLOWING THE LIQUID TO ESCAPE. THE TRANSFER AND SOLIDIFICATION WAS CONDUCTED WITHOUT INCIDENT AND ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT WAS PLACED INTO THE SECOND CONTAINER AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL SEALS AND CLOSURES WILL BE INSPECTED AND REPLACED IF FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE. IN ADDITION, ABSORBENT MATERIAL WILL BE PLACED AT THE DOOR OF ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS TO ACT AS A BARRIER AGAINST ANY MOISTURE THAT MAY ACCUMULATE AFTER LOADING IS COMPLETED BY THE SHIPPER.

THE DOCK ASSOCIATE WAS TRAINED IN THE PROPER HANDLING AND SECURING OF DRUMS WHEN USING A BARREL JACK.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WENT OFF THE ROAD ON RIGHT AND OVERTURNED.  RELIEF VALVE WAS BROKEN OFF BY ELECTRIC POLE.  LOST 359 GALLONS OF NITRIC ACID AT 67% SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME AND SODA ASH.  WAS IN RURAL AREA.  NO STREAMS OR DITCHES OR SEWER LINES.  WAS ABLE TO REMOVE LIME AND SOIL AFTER IT HAD BEEN TESTED NEUTRAL.  FIVE (5) EMERGENCY PEOPLE GOT INTO VAPORS.  ALL WERE TREATED AND RELEASED FROM AREA HOSPITAL.  OUR DRIVER WAS CONSCIOUS AND ABLE TO TALK.  HE TOLD RESCUE PERSONNEL WHAT HE WAS HAULING AND WHO THE SHIPPER AND CARRIER WERE.  GAVE PERSONNEL EMERGENCY PHONE LIST.  CARRIER OR SHIPPER WEREN'T NOTIFIED FOR THREE (3) HOURS.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE USING THE NEW 1993 EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK IN WHICH NITRIC ACID IS PROPERLY LISTED.

AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND FOUND THE SEALED TO BE MISSING AROUND THE FITTINGS.  NEW SEALS WERE INTSTALLED, BOTH TOTES WERE DECON AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.

DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO USE WRITE TO INSURE THE EARS DO NOT VIBRATE LOOSE AGIAN.  A HOSE FITTING WITH A SELF-LOCKING DEVICE WOULD PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: CLEAN UP DRIVER, CLYDE DAVID, CALLED AROUND 3:00 PM NEAR ALEXANDRIA, LA. WHILE PERFORMING HIS TIRE CHECK HE HAD DISCOVERED A DRIP FROM THE TRAILERS TAILGATE.  THE RATE OF DRIP WAS ABOUT EVERY THING SECONDS AND ONLY A VERY SMALL AMOUNT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER.  I ADVISED OUR DRIVER NOT TO MOVE HIS UNIT AND TO REMOVE AN MOISTURE FROM THE GROUND; TO PLACE PLASTIC ON THE GROUND AND TO INSERT RAGS UNDER THE END GATE WHERE THE DRIP WAS ORIGINATING TO STOP THE DRIP.  HE DID THIS AND FELT THAT HE HAD THE LEAD CONTAINED UNTIL A CREW COULD ARRIVE TO PLACE ABSORBANT IN THE TRAILER.  I THEN DISPATCHED TWO WORKERS TO THE LOCATION WITH OUR SPILL RESPONSE TRAILER TO SECURE THIS LOAD AND PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKING BY PLACING ABSORBANT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  I PLACED A CALL TO CHUCK HAMMOCK WITH LION OIL AND ADIVSED HIM OF THE SITUATION.  OUR WORKERS PLACED SIX 50 POUND BAGS OF OIL DRY AND TEN GALLONS OF FLYASH INSIDE THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO ABSORB ANY LIQUIDS THAT WERE PRESENT.  OUR DRIVER WAS THEN RELEASED AND PROCEEDED ON TO THE DISPOSAL DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  I MAILED A LETTER TO THE GENERATOR, LION OIL, OUTLINING THE ACTION TAKEN BY OUR COMPANY AND STRESSING THE IMPORTANCE OF PREVENTING THIS FORM REOCCURING AND A COPY OF THIS REPORT.  I ALSO REQUESTED IN WRITING WHAT ACTIONS WOULD BE IMPLEMENTED TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE.  ALSO, I AM SURE THAT YOU ARE AWARE OF THE IMPORTANCE OF TAKING CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT THIS FORM OCCURING AGAIN.  PLEASE FIND AN INVOICE FOR RESPONDING TO THIS LEAKING LOAD.

column168: THIS FOLLOW-UP REPORT IS FOR THE FACILITY LOCATED AT 1129 ROBERTS INDUSTRIAL DRIVE, BIRMINGHAM. ALABAMA INVOLVING THE ACCIDENTAL RELEASE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID 31% ON TUESDAY, MARCH 8, 1994.  THE COORDINATES OF THE FACILITY ARE APPROXIMATELY NORTH 33 DEGREE 31'-1.42" AND WEST 86 DEGREE 52'-13.02".  THE INITIAL REPORT OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IS ASSUMED TO HAVE BEEN MADE BY A SECURITY GUARD FROM ANOTHER BUSINESS IN THE AREA AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30PM.  THE FAILITY MANAGER, JOHNNY RECTOR RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AT 9:40PM.  HE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 10:10PM, ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND INITATED CALLS TO OTHER PERSONNEL WITHIN OUR ORGANIZATION FOR RESPONDED AND CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.  THE INCIDENT CONCLUDED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30AM.  WEATHER CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE WERE NO RAIN, HIGH SCATTERED CLOUDS, TEMPERATURE 54 DEGREES, BAROMETRIC PRESSURE 29.96 AND THE WIND WAS FROM THE NORTHEAST AT 10MPH.  UPON ARRIVAL, MR. RECTOR OBSERVED RESPONSE UNITS FROM STATION 16, 18 AND A HOOK AND LADDER UNIT POSSIBLY FROM STATION 20. THE ENSLEY PRECINCT DISPATCHED SERVERAL UNITS TO THE INTERSECTIONS OF 13TH STREET AND AVENUE V AND BROCK INDUSTIAL DRIVE AND AN UNNAMED SERVICE ROAD TO THE NORTH OF 13TH STREET.  ANOTHER POLICE UNIT WAS OBSERVED AT ANNISTON AVENUE WHICH IS A RESIDENTIAL AREA APPROXIMATELY 1180 FEET FROM THE SITE. ALL UNITS WERE PLACED ON STAND-BY AT A CONSIDERABLE DISTANCE FROM THE FACILITY UNTIL THE PROBLEM WAS DETERMINED AND RESOLVED.  INITIALLY, THE EVACUATION OF THE HOMES ALONG 15TH STREET, ADJACENT TO AND SOUTH OF 13TH STREET WAS ORDERED,  SHORLTY THEREAFTER, WHEN THE STRENGTH OF THE HYDROCHLORIC WAS DETERMINED, THE EVACUATION WAS TERMINATED.  THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE OCCURED FROM A PORTABLE TOTE TANK WITH A 320 GALLON CAPACITY. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 120 TO 130 GALLONS OR 1250 POUNDS WERE RECOVERED FROM THE AREA OF THE SPILL.  SOME OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TANK WAS INITALLY TRANSFERRED TO PLASTIC BUCKETS AND THEN INTO A DRUM.  THE TANK WAS THEN TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO STOP THE PRODUCT FROM ESCAPING THEN TAKING TO A CONTAINMENT AREA FOR TRANSFER TO DRUMS.  THE HYDROCHLORIC WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED USING SODIUM CARBONATE.  ONCE ALL THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED BY THE SODIUM CARBONATE IT WAS TRANSFERRED TO DRUMS AND MOVED TO AN AREA PROTECTED FROM THE WEATHER,  THE AREA OF THE SPILL WAS AGAIN SCRAPED AND SWEPT TO REMOVE ANY REMAINING RESIDUE.  NO PRODUCT FROM THE RELEASE ENTERED SURFACE DRAINS.  WE SUSPECT THAT THE LEAK IN THE PORTABLE TANK WAS CAUSED BY THE INSTALLATION OF AN INCOMPATIBLE FITTING.  THE TANK WAS INSPECTED ON MONDAY, MARCH 7TH AND FOUND TO HAVE A DEFECTIVE VALVE ASSEMBLY.  A NEW VALVE ASSEMBLY INCLUDING THE DEFECTIVE 3" NIPPLE WAS INSTALLED.  THIS 3" NIPPLE WAS APPARENTLY INCOMPATIBLE WITH THE ACID AND FOUND TO BE SUBSTANTIALLY DETERIORATED.  THE FITTING, MADE OF VINYL, HAD NO DISTINGUISHABLE MARKS TO DIFFERENTIATE IT FROM OTHER PVC FITTINGS.  WE HAVE CONFIRMED THIS BEING THE
DRIVER OVER FILLED DUE TO WEAK WHISTLE DEBREE CLEANED OUT OF VENT LINE.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AND IMMEDIATELY STRUCK THE TANKS. TANK ONE WAS AT 57 1/4 INCHES CONVERTED TO 6235 GALLONS. TANK TWO WAS AT 58 INCHES CONVERTED TO 6334 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER HAD 7800 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. WITH THE PRIOR READINGS AND THE AMOUNT DELIVERED THE AMOUNT WOULD HAVE BEEN 20,369 GALLONS IN TWO 10,000 GALLON TANKS. THE DRIVER TRIED TO DROP TOO MUCH PRODUCT INTO ONE TANK AND THE PRODUCT DID NOT BLEED INTO THE OTHER QUICKLY ENOUGH. THE PRODUCT CAME BACK OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TANK RESULTING IN THE SPILL. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY DRIVER WITH SPILL PADS WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

FREIGHT WAS IN OS&D AS OFF - ROUTE FREIGHT WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THAT A CORNER OF THE TOP OF THE BOX APPEARED TO BE WET. THE BOX WAS OPENED AND THE PLASTIC JUG INSIDE THE BOX WAS EXAMINED AND WAS FOUND TO HAVE A DRY WHITE SUBSTANCE ON THE JUG CAP. APPARENTLY THE TOP OF THE JUG LEAKED DUE TO THE CAP BEING LOOSE. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND BOX TAPED UP AND SENT TO THE DESTINATION ADDRESS. SHIPPERS SHOULD ENSURE THAT CONTAINERS ARE TRAVEL-WORTHY BEFORE BEING OFFERED FOR TRANSPORT.

DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING THE PALLETIZING FREIGHT WHEN HE DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED BAGS. APPARENTLY DURING THE LOADING PROCESS AT THE ORIGIN TERMINAL THE BAGS WERE RIPPED OPEN BY THE ACTION OF ANOTHER SKID OF FREIGHT CATCHING THE BOTTOM BAGS WHILE THE SKIDS WERE BEING PLACED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. BAGS WERE TAPED UP AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION TERMINAL. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPED IN PAPER BAGS ARE JUST TOO SUSCEPTIBLE TO DAMAGE DURING THE NORMAL COURSE OF HANDLING AND TRANSPORTING. BAGS NEED TO BE PLACED IN PROTECTIVE SHIPPING CONTAINERS TO PREVENT DAMAGE.

column168: ON MARCH 25, 1994 AT APPROXIMATELY 05:00 WE SPOTTED SUPERIOR CARRIER TRAILER #21369 AT OLIN CORP PLANT FACILITY TO BE PRELOADED FOR DELIVERY MARCH 28, 1994 TO NUTRASWEET COMPANY.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED AND THEN SPOTTED ON OLIN CORP DROP PAD.  THE DROP PAD IS A CONTAINED PAD WHICH DRAINS INTO ONE OF THEIR HOLDING PONDS IN THE EVENT OF A SPILL.  AT 15:45 MARCH 25, 1994 I WAS NOTIFIED BY OLIN CORP THAT SUPERIOR CARRIER TRAILER #21369 WAS LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID OUT OF THE LEFT SIDE, DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE DROP PAD.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE PLANT SITE WITH ANOTHER TRAILER, WE TRANSLOADED THE PRODUCT IMMEDIATELY.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 TO 3 GALLON LOSS OF PRODUCT.  THE LOADED TRAILER WAS ON THE DROP PAD ABOUT 10 HOURS BEFORE IT DEVELOPED THE LEAK.  THE TRAILER WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO AN AUTHORIZED REPAIR FACILITY FOR FULL INVESTIGATION AS TO WHY THE RUBBER LINING APPARENTLY FAILED TO KEEP THE PRODUCT FROM DOING DAMAGE TO THE SHELL OF THE TRAILER.

HE, BY MISTAKE, BROKE THE CONNECTION ON THE OUTLET SIDE OF THE PUMP, RESULTING IN SPILL.

column168: INVESTIGATION OF THE ACCIDENT SHOWS THAT THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING SOUTH ON CALAGHAN ROAD FROM THEBRSICOE D LEASE.  THE DRIVER STATE THAT HE HAD LOADED 190 BBLS. OF CONDENSATE AT THE BRISCOE D.  IT IS 2.5 MILES FROM THE TANK TO THE GATE ON CALAGHAN RD.  THE DRIVER STATES HE REMEMBERS PASSING THE FIRST PILE NEAR THE BRISCOE B.  HE ALSO STATE THAT HE REMEMBERS THE PILES OF CALICHE BEING PRESENT N HIS LAST VISIT TO THIS AREA.  THE DRIVER STATES THAT HE MUST HAVE "DOZED OFF" JUST PRIOR TO RUNNING INTO THE CALICHE PILE.  HE STATED THAT THERE WAS NO OTHER TRAFFIC ON THE ROAD AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  HE ALSO STATED TO ME IN A TELEPHONE CONVERSATION IN THE PRESENCE OF LEON LOPEZ, ON MARCH 24, 1994, THAT HIS DAY UP TO THAT POINT HAD BEEN OTHERWISE NORMAL, THAT HE HAD NO UNUSUAL OUTSIDE STRESS FACTORS, AND THAT HE WAS FEELING FINE AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  HE COULD OFFER NO FURTHER EXPLANATION FOR THE ACCIDENT THAN THE FACT HE MUST HAVE "DOZED OFF" FOR A SECOND.  THE TRUCK STRUCK THE END OF THE CALICHE PILE HAD A FAIR RATE OF SPEED, JUDGED BY THE AMOUNT OF DAMAGE TO THE FRONT END OF THE TRACTOR.  DRIVER STATE THAT HE WAS TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 35MPH.  THERE IS NOT A XATA COMPUTER IN THIS VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE PASSED OVER THE CALICHE PILE FOR APPROXIMATELY 75 FEET.  THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR UPON COMING TO REST, ROLLED OVER ON THE DRIVER SIDE. THE TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED IN TWO PLACES, APPARENTLY BY THE TRACTOR FRAME BEHIND THE FIFTH WHEEL IN THE AREA OF THE DRIVE WHEELS.  THE FAILURE OF THE TANK RESULTED IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 123 BARRELS OF CONDENSATE WITH AN A.P.I. GRAVITY OF 51.  THE SPILL EXTENDED ACROSS THE ROAD ALONG THE DITCH FOR 1000 X 3-4 X UNKNOWN DEPTH FEET.  ROBERT (DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED SERIOUSLY IN THE ACCIDENT.  HE WAS SEEN BY A PHYSICIAN ON MARCH 23, 1994.  HE HAS A BRUISED LEFT SHOULDER. ROBERT STATED THAT ALL OF HIS VITAL SIGNS AND THE REMAINDER OF HIS PHYSICIAN EXAM WAS NORMAL.

THE OBJECT CAUSING THE PUNCTURE IS UNKNOWN.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

A FLATBED TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTING A 610 GALLON DOT-E 8839 POLY TANK CONTAINING 250 GALLONS OF 15% HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION FROM CROWLEY, LA. TO VENICE, LA DOCK.  A PVC NIPPLE ON THE DISCHARGE LINE CRACKED CAUSING THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK TO LEAK ON THE ROADWAY.  WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAK, HE NOTIFIED THE VENICE POLICE DEPARTMENT AND HIS MAIN OFFICE. THE WESTERN COMPANY DISPATCHED MATERIAL MANAGEMENT GROUP TO THE SCENE FOR ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP.  THE TANK HAD BEEN VISUALLY AND HYDROSTATICALLY TESTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 FCR 173.28 AND 173.32(F).  ALL PVC NIPPLES ON THE BOTTOM DISCHARGE HAVE BEEN REPLACED.  FABRICATION OF A SUPPORT HAD BEEN ADDED TO THE DISCHARGE LINE TO ELIMINATE NIPPLE AND FLANGE VIBRATION.

DRIVER BEGAN UNLOADING AND DISCOVERED A LEAKING CLAMP ON THE CONSIGNEES ULOADING LINE.  DRIVER STOPPED UNLOADING AND CLOSED ALL VALVES.  DRIVER NOTIFIED PLANT OPERATOR UNLOADING RESUMED AFTER CONSIGNEE REPAIRED UNLOADING LINE AND CLEANED UP VERY SMALL SPILL.

ICE THAT HAD FORMED IN THE ROLL-OFF BOX IN WARREN, MICHIGAN BEGAN TO MELT BY THE TIME IT ARRIVED IN LAS VEGAS, NEVADA.  UNKNOWN TO THE DRIVER WAS THE FACT THAT THERE WAS A SMALL CRACK IN THE SEAM WELD ON THE BOTTOM OF THE ROLL-OFF BOX.  THE DRIVER PARKED THE TRACTOR TO GO OFF-DUTY.  DURING HIS TIME OFF-DUTY SOMEONE REPORTED THE ROLL-OFF BOX DRIPPING. ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES OF NEVADA, INC.  WAS CALLED TO THE SITE.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO PUTY THE CRACK AND CONTINUE TO U.S. ECOLOGY IN BEATTY, NEVADA.  THE SMALL QUANTITY OF LIQUID THAT DRIPPED WAS CLEANED UP WITH SOME RAGS.  AT U.S. ECOLOGY THE BOX WAS DISPOSED OF ALONG WITH ALL THE MATERIAL IN IT, INCLUDING THE RAGS THAT WERE USED.

THE DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF #1 FUEL OIL INTO A BULK PLANT HORIZANTAL STORAGE TANK WITH A CAPACITY OF 10,000 GALLONS.  THE TANK GAUGE INDICATED THERE WERE 834 INCHES OF PRODUCTION.  THE DRIVER BEGINING DELIVERING.  AFTER THE DRIVER HAD DELIVERED APPROXIMATELY 6500 GALLONS OUT OF 7600 GALLONS.  THE END OF THE STORAGE TANK BLEW OFF. THIS RELEASED 6500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO THE GROUND.  POLICE AND FIRE OFFICIALS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  STATE OF SOUTH DAKOTA DNR WAS NOTIFIED AND GEM STAIR ASSOCIATES OF WAVBAY, SD WERE CONTACTED FOR CLEAN UP.  THIS TANK WAS IMPROPERLY VENTED.  THIS CAUSED THE PRESSURE BUILD UP AND RESULTING BLOW OUT.  PROPER VENTING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY OUR COMAPNY FROM POWER SERVICE PRODUCTS, INC. ONE MARCH 24, 1994, WITH A SCHEDULED DELIVERY AT UNITED OIL OF MAGIC IN CALDWELL, ID ON MARCH 28, 1994.  THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED THIRTY TWO, 55 GALLON DRUMS OF "FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. (HYDROXY COMPOUNDS)UN 1993".  ON MARCH 27, 1994, AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 CST, OUR DRIVER RUBEN ACOSTA STOPPED AT THE FLYING J TRUCKSTOP IN BOISE, ID, AND NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY PARKED THE TRACTOR/TRAILER AWAY FROM OTHER VEHICLES AND PEOPLE AND CALLED OUR 24 HOUR SAFETY HOTLINE. AFTER HE REPORTED THE INCIDENT, THE EMERGENCY CONTACT (CHEMTREC), THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND IDAHO STATE POLICE WERE CALLED, TO DETERMINE WHAT ACTION SHOULD BE TAKEN AND, TO SEAL OFF THE AREA.  WHEN THE TRAILER DOORS WERE OPENED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE 55 GALLONS DRUMS HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE LOOSE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE OTHER DRUMS WERE INSPECTED FOR LOOSE FITTINGS CAPS.  THE BOISE FIRE DEPARTMENT WIPED UP WHAT THEY COULD IN THE TRAILER AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO USE OIL DRY OT A SIMILAR ABSORBANT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR ONCE HE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 20 MILES AWAY.  THE STATE POLICE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED, THAT DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE MATERIAL IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO CALL IN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAN-UP CREW BECAUSE THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND (APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT) WOULD DISSIPATE IN A SHORT TIME AND WOULD NOT CREATE AN ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARD. AT 2330 CST, THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED AND CONTINUED ON TO HIS DELIVERY. POWER SERVICE PRODUCTS, INC. RECEIVED A COMPLETE REPORT OF THE INCIDENT AND MADE A COMMITMENT TO INSPECT ALL DRUMS BEFORE LOADING.  WE FEEL CONFIDENT THAT THIS IS AN ISOLATED INCIDENT DUE THE NUMBER OF LOADS THAT WE TRANSPORT FOR THIS SHIPPER AND UP TO THIS POINT WE HAVE NOT HAVE A RELEASE OR SPILL OF ANY KIND.  THEY HAVE AGREED TO EXAMINE ALL ASPECTS OF THE SHIPMENTS IN ORDER TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS.

OUR LOCAL DRIVER WAS DRIVING DOWN RT 298E WHEN THIS TANK BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE VALVE. THIS VALVE WAS RECESSED FROM THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND WAS NOT STICKING OUT WHERE IT COULD BE HIT OR KNOCKED. THE VALVE ITSELF SEPERATED FROM THE TANK DUE TO THE VIBRATION OF TRAVELING AND MATERIAL FATIQUE CAUSING THE CORROSIVE LIQUID TO LEAK OUT.

WHILE UNLOADING THE ULD, ONE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. UPON OPENING THE CARTON IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ALL OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS WERE INTACT. EXAMINING CLOSER, THE SEALS ON 3 BOTTLES MUST NOT HAVE BEEN TIGHT. WHEN PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO THE SEALS NO MORE LEAKAGE OCCURED. SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO EXXON COMPAMY USA LOCATED AT 4115 BUELL STREET IN CHESAPEAKE, VA TO PICK UP A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, N.O.S. (GASOLINE TANK WATER BOTTOMS). UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE DRIVER AND THE SITE SUPERVISOR INITIATED THE STEPS NECESSARY TO CONDUCT THE TRANSFER OF MATERIAL FROM A STORAGE TANK INTO 6000 GALLON CARGO, TANK LOCATED 120 FEET APART. TO ACCOMPLISH THE TRANSFER, THE PRODUCT WAS DRAINED FROM THE STORAGE TANK INTO AN OPEN TOP 55 GALLON DRUM AND SIMULTANEOUSLY PUMPED INTO THE VACUUM TRAILER. THROUGHOUT THIS OPERATION, THE DRIVER WAS ATTENDING THE VACUUM TRAILER WHILE THE SITE SUPERVISOR CONTROLLED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT INTO THE 55 GALLON DRUM. AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, HOWEVER, THE SITE SUPERVISOR HAD WALKED APPROXIMATELY 40 FEET FROM THE 55 GALLON DRUM IN ORDER TO INSPECT THE TRANSFER HOSE. AS HE RETURNED TOWARDS THE DRUM, HE NOTICED THAT THE LEVEL OF PRODUCT WAS APPROACHING THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER. HE IMMEDIATELY REACHED FOR THE HOSE IN ORDER TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT BUT DROPPED THE HOSE SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND. THE OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES WERE INITIATED. ALL FREE LIQUID WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO THE VACUUM TRAILER FOR DISPOSAL AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. APPROXIMATELY 2 CUBIC YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND IS BEING STORED ON SITE PENDING DISPOSAL APPROVAL AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, THE SITE SUPERVISOR HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO ATTEND THE OPEN TOP DRUM AT ALL TIMES. IN THE EVENT HE/SHE NEEDS TO ATTEND TO ORDER DUTIES, THE OPERATION IS TO BE INTERRUPTED UNTIL SUCH TIME THAT THE SUPERVISOR CAN RESUME THE MONITORING OF THE DRUM. IN ADDITION, AN OPEN TOP DRUM WITH A LARGER CAPACITY WILL BE UTILIZED AND PLACED ONTO A PALLET LINED WITH ABSORBENT PADS. FINALLY, THE SUCTION HOSE WILL BE SECURED TO THE DRUM TO PREVENT IT FROM BEING DISLODGED DURING THE PUMPING OPERATION.

THE DRIVERS ARE BEING RETRAINED AS TO THE PROPER LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES INVOLVED IN THESE CHEMICALS. STEP-BY-STEP INSTRUCTIONS BY A COMPANY APPROVED SUPERVISOR.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION BUT WAS TOLD THAT THEY WERE NOT SURE IF THEIR STORAGE WOULD HOLD THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL BEING DELIVERED. THEIR STORAGE FILLED  BEFORE ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS DELIVERED AND OUR DRIVER WAS TOLD TO SHUT DOWN BUT TO KEEP HIS UNLOADING HOSE CONNECTED SINCE IT WAS FULL OF PRODUCT. OUR DRIVER WAITED FOR 9 HOURS BEFORE THEY ADVISED HIM TO CONTINUE HIS DELIVERY. HE STARTED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL BUT AFTER A TIME HE WAS INFORMED THAT THAT NO PRODUCT WAS ENTERING THEIR STORAGE. HE DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT IN THE HOSE HAD SET UP DUE TO THE DELAY. HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO DISLODGE THE BLOCKAGE WHEN THE HOSE DISCONNECTED AND THERE WAS A SPILL. HE NOTIFIED THE RECEIVER AND WAS TOLD NOT TO WORRY ABOUT IT SINCE IT WAS THEIR FAULT FOR DELAYING THE DELIVERY AND THEY CLEANED UP THE SPILL AREA.

column168: TANK CAR FOUND TO BE LEAKING BY FRA INSPECTOR RADER DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION AT CLOVIS YARD.  SOURCES OF LEAK WERE 1) VALVE NOT SEATED/CLOSED (TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN) 2) NO PACKING UNDER PACKING GLAND NUT ON TOBOV STEM; 3) TWO BOLTS SHEARED OFF FROM THE REDUCER FLANGE TO TANK CAR TANK MOUNTING.  VALVE TIGHTENED AND REMAINING BOLTS ON FLANGE TIGHTENED, BUT LEAK WAS NOT FULLY STOPPED. CAR WAS SPOTTED TO FUEL AREA DRIP PADS THEN UNLOADED.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND IS BEING AERIATED.

WHILE UNLOADING HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION AT BRONSON, MI OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO HOOK A 2 FOOT LONG 2" PLASTIC (OVC) PIPE FLANGED ON BOTH ENDS WITH AN AIR BLOW-OFF CONNECTION AND IS USED TO SHUT DOWN THE PRODUCT AFTER FILLING ONE TANK, BLOW OUT THE HOSE THEN HOOK TO A SECOND TANK AND FINISH OFF LOADING.  OUR DRIVER AND A MR. LLOYD SAXTON, THE UNLOADER, WERE BOTH AT THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK WHEN THE PVC 2" PIPE BROKE AND SPLASHED HCL ON BOTH MEN.  OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE EMERGENCY VALVE AND THEN WASHED OFF WITH WATER.  THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEE WENT INSIDE AND GOT IN THE SHOWER.  HIS COMPANY TOOK HIM TO THE HOSPITAL TO GET CHECKED OUT.  OUR DRIVER THEY TOLD HIM THAT THE UNLOADER WAS RELEASED AND BACK AT THE PLANT BY THE TIME HE FINISHED UNLOADING.  THE CONSIGNEE PUT TWO BAGS OF SODA ASH ON THE SPILL THEN SCRAPED UP ABOUT 2 CUBIC YARDS OF GRAVEL AND SODA ASH MIXTURE AND PUT IT INTO CONTAINERS AND TOOK IT TO THEIR WASTE TREATMENT PLANT FOR NEUTRALIZATION.

column168: OUR COMPANY OWNED SEMI-TRUCK AND CARGO TANK WITH PUP CARRYING 12,000 GALS OF NO. 2 DIESEL FUEL WENT OFF THE ROADWAY AND ROLLED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT. THE ACCIDENT WAS ATTRIBUTED TO THE DRIVER FALLING ASLEEP.  IMMEDIATE RESPONSE BY INITIAL PEOPLE ON THE SCENE PROMPTLY ASSEMBLED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES AND EQUIPMENT TO CONTAIN, RECOVER AND CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE CONOCO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM AND A SUPERVISOR FROM FARSTAD OIL, INC.  ARRIVED WITHIN 20 MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT.  THEY BEGAN CONSTRUCTION A DIKE TO CONTAIN SPILLAGE WHICH HAD COME FROM THE PUP, MAINLY AFTER COMING TO REST.  COUNTY PERSONNEL ARRIVED WITH A BACKHOE TO COMPLETE THE DIKE WITHIN AN HOUR OF THE INCIDENT.  PUMP TRUCKS WERE BROUGHT OUT TO BEGIN UNLOADING THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE OVERTURNED TRAILERS INTO ANOTHER TRUCK.  OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. CONTRACTED FOR HAZARDOUS CLEANUP, WAS ON THE SCENE AND BEGAN RECOVERING POOLED PRODUCT WITH ABSORBANT PADS.  ALL REQUIRED AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS WERE COMPLETE BY FARSTAD OIL PERSONNEL ON MARCH 24, 1994.  SAME AS REPORT #94041285A.

THE PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED FRIDAY MORNING AT THE FEDERAL EXPRESS MEMPHIS HUB ON FLIGHT A/C 267 IN CONTAINER SAA 0687. A STRONG GASOLINE OR JET FUEL TYPE ODOR WAS APPARENTLY EMANATING FROM THE DRUM AND DANGEROUS GOODS HUB PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED. THEY NOTIFIED DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED DR. ROY PARKER, RADIATION PHYSICS CONSULTANT, AT 3:27 AM CT, FRIDAY, MARCH 18, 1994. ALTHOUGH AN ODOR WOULD NOT BE INDICATIVE OF A RADIATION PROBLEM, IT COULD BE INDICATIVE OF NON-DECLARED HAZARD. DR. PARKER HAD THE HUB DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST CHECK EXTERNAL RADIATION LEVELS FROM THE DRUM AND THEY WERE SATISFACTORY. HE INSTRUCTED THE HUB DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST TO PUT ON GLOVES AND OPEN THE DRUM UNDER HIS INSTRUCTION. WHEN THE DRUM WAS OPENED IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS EMANATING FROM INSIDE THE DRUM, WHICH CONTAINED A FLUID PUMP AND A PLASTIC BAG CONTAINING SOAKED PAPER TOWELS AND OTHER MATERIALS. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE PLASTIC BAG WAS THE PRINCIPAL SOURCE OF RADIATION AND WIPE TESTS REVEALED THAT THE BAG AND INTERIOR OF THE DRUM WERE CONTAMINATED. THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST WAS INSTRUCTED TO CLOSE THE DRUM. THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE DRUM WAS WIPED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT PORTIONS OF THE OUTER SURFACE ON THE DRUM WERE CONTAMINATED THAT PORTIONS OF THE OUTER SURFACE ON THE DRUM WERE CONTAMINATED. THE SPECIALIST WAS INSTRUCTED TO PLACE THE DRUM IN A PLASTIC BAG TO PREVENT SPREAD OF CONTAMINATION AND TO PLACE GLOVES AND ANY CONTAMINATED ITEMS IN THE BAG. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SECURED HUB DANGEROUS GOODS HOLDING BUILDING. THE INBOUND AIRCRAFT WAS LOCATED AND SURVEYED FOR CONTAMINATION WITH  NEGATIVE RESULTS AND EFFORTS WERE INITIATED TO LOCATE THE CONTAINER WHICH CONTAINED THE INBOUND PACKAGE. FAA/CASFO WAS NOTIFIED AT 4:37 AM CT. DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION SAFETY SPECIALIST LOCATED CONTAINER SAA 0687 LATER FRIDAY MORNING, SURVEYED IT AND THERE WAS NO DETECTABLE CONTAMINATION. THE ENCLOSED TYPE A PACKAGE DOCUMENTATION WAS REQUESTED FROM TRU-TEK AND IT IS NOTED THAT THE INNER PACKAGE WAS NOT THE DESCRIBED LEAD CONTAINER, BUT A PUMP, AND THAT THERE WAS NO FOAM INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD UNTIL THURSDAY, APRIL 7, 1994 AND INSTRUCTIONS WERE ISSUED TO SURVEY THE PACKAGE FOR SURFACE CONTAMINATION, AND IF THERE WAS NO DETECTABLE ACTIVITY TO RELEASE THE PACKAGE FOR SHIPMENT TO TRU-TEK, NEWARK, DELAWARE. BASED ON CALCULATIONS THE SURFACE CONTAMINATION SHOULD BE WELL BELOW REGULATORY LIMITS ON THURSDAY. APRIL 7, 1994.

ONE DRUM WAS FOUND THAT DID NOT HAVE (OR APPEAR TO HAVE) PRESSURE.  THE BUNG SEALS WERE CHECKED, THEN REAPPLIED AND TIGHTENED.  THE ONE SUSPECT DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE LOAD AND OVERPACKED TO RETURN TO THE SHIPPER FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  LOAD RELEASED.  SHIPPER'S INSPECTION OF DRUM DID NOT FIND ANY PROBLEM LIKELY ONELY LOOSE BUNG.  NO PRODUCT WAS FOUND, ONLY THE STENCH OF THE VAPOR SEEPING PAST THE SLIGHTLY LOOSE BUNG.

column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN THE MATERIAL SPLASHED OUT OF AN IMPROPERLY SEALED MANWAY ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY LESS THAN 100 GALLONS RELEASED.  THE MARION COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT, THE WAYNE TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPT (INCLUDING THE HAZMAT TEAM), AND SEVERAL AMBUALNCES RESPONDED.  MATERIAL SPLASHED ON TWO PASSING VEHICLES. ONE VEHICLE WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED IN A CAR WSH; THE OTHER WAS PRESSURE WASHED BY THE REPSONDING REMEDIATION COMPANY.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL APPARENTLY SPLASHED ON THE ARM OF A PASSENGER OF ONE OF THE VEHICLES CAUSING SKIN IRITATION.  THIS INDIVIDUAL WAS SENT FORM THE SCENE IN AN AMBULANCE TO A LOCAL HSOPITAL.  HERITAGE REMIDIATION/ENGINEERING, INC (HR/E) WAS CALLED ON SITE TO REMEDIATE THE RELEASE.  HR/E PRESSURE WASHED WASHINGTON STREET WHERE THE MATERIAL SPILLED.  THE ROADWAY WAS REOPENED AT 19:30 ON THE SAME DAY.   NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE SEWER SYTEM OR TO ANY WATERWAY. THE WASH WATER WAS COLLECTED BY A VACUUM TRUCK AND DISPOSED OF BY THE HERITAGE ENVIRONMENT SERVICES, INC. TREATMENT CENTER LOCATED AT 7901 WEST MORRIS STREET IN INDIANAPOLIS.  THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, THE INDIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, AND THE MARION COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT DIVISION.  INFORMATION WAS ALSO GIVEN TO THE MARION COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT.  THE INJURED PART WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE.  HERITAGE TRANSPORT, INC. IS NOT AWARE IF THE INJURED PARTY WAS ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL.

column168: I MADE A PERSONAL VISIT TO MERRY MAIDS ON 3-21-94, TO DISCUSS A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED ON 3-10-94. ONE OF THEIR PACKAGES CONTAINING TOILET BOWL CLEANER WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE AND AN INCOMPATIBLE MATERIAL WAS LOADED ON TOP OF THE CARTON CAUSING THE PACKAGE TO BE CRUSHED.  AFTER RECIEVING THE DAMAGED PACKAGE, ALL SHIPPING AND PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS WERE MET BY THE CUSTOMER.  THE INCOMPATIBLE MATERIAL SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF THIS PACKAGE.

CLOSURE ON METAL CAN NOT COMPLETELY TIGHT. VERY SMALL AMOUNT LEAKED OUT. BOX THAT THE 5 GAL PAIL WAS IN WAS ENTIRELY TOO BIG. NEEDED A SMALLER BOX OR ADDITIONAL CUSHIONING. ALL DMP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED.

WE RECEIVED A CALL AT 01:35 ABOUT A LEAKING HAZARDOUS PACKAGE ON 27 DOOR IN A BROCKTON VAN. AFTER CONSULTING THE DECISION TREE I RESPONDED WEARING PPE. I PLACED THE WET BOX IN A PREPARED SPILL TUB BROUGHT IT TO THE DMP AREA. I PROCESSED THE DAMAGED MATERIALS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL CLASSIFICATION THROUGH THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM. I REPACKED THE UNDAMAGED CONTENTS AND SHIPPED THEM TO THE CONSIGNEE. CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED AT 04:25.
PACKAGE HAD A LOOSE CAP. HAD VERY LITTLE SPILLAGE, WAS PROCESSED IN PROPER MANNOR.

AFTER COMPLETING THE FIRST PART OF A BREAK BULK DELIVERY, THE VENT HATCH ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER WAS LEFT UNLATCHED, AS THE TANKER LEFT THE SITE OF DELIVERY, THE PRODUCT SURGE, WHICH OCCURS DUE TO THE MOTION AND CHANGE IN SPEED OF THE TANKER, CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 20-25 GALLON OF MATERIAL TO SPLASH OUT OF THE VENT HATCH. AS THE TANKER PROCEEDED DOWN THE STREET IT LEFT A TRAIL OF MATERIAL FOR A DISTANCE OF TWO AND ONE HALF (2 1/2) BLOCKS. LOCAL FIRE COMPANY'S AND A RESPONSE TEAM FROM NORTH INDUSTRIAL CHEMICALS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND PROCEDURES FOR A CLEANUP WERE STARTED. ALL PROCEDURES WERE APPROVED BY A LOCAL EPA REPRESENTATIVE WHO WAS ALSO ON THE SCENE. A MORE DETAILED CHECKLIST OF LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES WILL BE DRAWN UP TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS AND NO INJURIES.

column168: WHILE MAKING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE IN COMPANY OF CIEF INSPECTOR AAR, MR. A.D. MATY NOTED EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT HAVEING SPLASHED FROM THE SAFETY VENT BEING MOUNTED ON THE CENTER MANWAY NOZZLE ON CAR GATX 41065.  CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH THREE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  CAR EQUIPPED WIHT A "GATX 261-53" DISC RETAINER/ SPLASH DEFLECTOR.  DISMANTLED SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY AND NOT EQUIPPED WITH ANY TYPE OF SURGE BAFFLE.  THE SWING BOLT TO THE LEFT OF THE HINGE SIDE ON THE NOZZLE HAD THE THREADS STRIPPED MIDWAY OF THE BOLT AND THE BOT COULD BE DISENGAGED WITHOUT ANY EFFORT. THE COVER PLATE HAS FOUR SWING BOLTS ALL OF WHICH WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  THE SWING BOLT BRACKET WELDS ON THE NOZZLE WERE BROKEN ALLOWING THE BOLT TO HAVE CONSIDERABLE "PLAY" BEFORE BECOMING FULLY ENGAGED FOR TIGHTENING.  THE "O" RING TYPE NOZZLE GASKET HAD APPROXIMATELY 1/3 RD HANGING OUTSIDE THE NOZZLE (POSSIBLY CAUSED BY PRODUCT SURGE EITHER BEFORE OR AFTER THE DISC FAILED).  OPENED COVER PLATE AND WAS ABLE TO REPOSITION THE GASKET.  REMOVED THE NUT FROM THE STRIPPED BOLT AND APPLIED THREE WASHERS WHICH ALLOWED PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE COVER PLATE. CHEMTREC WAS ADVISED AT 1710 HOURS, MR. TOM FLORES REPORT #27209.  MR. AL KELLY, HDC WAS ADVISED AT 1805 HOURS.  MARCH 3,10994 MR. FRED ADAMS AT TEXAS GULF WAS FURNISHED INFORMATION RELATIVE TO THIS INCIDENT.  SHIPMENT WAS CONTRARY TO 173.31 (B) (1 AND 3) AND 172.204 (A) TITLE 49CFR, FOR SHIPPER FAILURE TO PROPERLY SECURE MANWAY COVER, AND FAILURE TO REPLACE A DEFECTIVE BOLTING/THREADED ELEMENT (STRIPPED EYEBOLT AND BROKEN WELDED EYEBOLT BRACKET).

CHEMTREC AND STAN ANDERSON OF KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column26: ABE HALL RD P O BOX 339
column168: DISPATCHER AT HDC, OMAHA CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER R. M. STINE AT 2100 HOURS ADVISING TRAIN NLNP-04 WAS ON PASSING TRACK AT OSAWATOMIE, KANSAS FURTHER THEY HAD RECEIVED A CITIZEN COMPLAINT OF AN AMMONIA ODOR NEAR THE ROW. MTO PAUL JOLLY HAD BEEN SENT TO AREA AT 1700 HOURS AND LOCATED CAR TGPX 33602, 86TH REAR CAR IN TRAIN, HAVING A VAPOR COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, ALSO A SMALL LIQUID STREAM RUNNING DOWN SIDE OF CAR. ON GROUND INSPECTION BY MR. STINE IN COMPANY OF MR A.D. MATY CHIEF INSPECTOR AAR NOTED FROST ON OUTSIDE OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING TOWARD "B" END. REMOVED INTACT SHIPPER SEAL UP V 671666 AND OPENED COVER NOTING LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE STEM. CAR EQUIPPED WITH "3" JAMESBURY ANGLE BALL VALVES. REMOVED VALVE HANDLE AND TIGHTENED THE TWO NUTS ON THE VALVE PACKING RETAINER WHICH SECURED THE STEM LEAK. ALSO NOTED THAT THE PORT PLUG WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. AFTER CHECKING ALL FITTINGS CHECKED WITH "SNOOP" LEAK DETECTOR AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE. CONTACTED HDC OMAHA, AND ADVISED THAT REPAIR OF LEAKING CAR WAS COMPLETE AND ASKED THEY CONTACT CHEMTREC, WHICH WAS DONE BY MARK PETERSON AT 2144 HOURS (WASHINGTON TIME).

AT 0030 HOURS ON 3-51-94, CTS MGR. LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY SPECIAL AGENT ART GARDNER. HE ADVISED THAT A CARMAN HAD REPORTED LOADED TANK CAR TGPX 33608, LOCATED ON WEST RECEIVING TRACK 5; CONTAINING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, LIQUEFIED; LEAKING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. ON ARRIVAL AT SCENE, MGR. LERCH NOTED VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND HOUSING TO BE FROST COVERED. INSPECTION OF FITTINGS REVEALED PRODUCT TO BE LEAKING FROM THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WITH THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS NOTED. BALL VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN, VALVE PLUG NOT WRENCH TIGHT, VALVE PACKING LOOSE. UPON CLOSING VALVE, TIGHTENING PACKING AND PLUG 1 1/2 TURNS, RELEASE WAS STOPPED. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURES OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE. NOTIFICATIONS: 0355 HRS 3-5-94, UPRR M.D.I. STAN KINSTLEY; 0400 HRS NE. STATE PATROL, #H9401178, 0405HRS, NE. D.E.Q., JOM BOROVICH, #030394-JB-0405; 0410HRS, CHEM-TREC, TOM FLORES, #27252; 0830HRS, 3-7-94, FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, OFFICE MGR. BOB BROWNING; 0945HRS, UPRR E.M.G. MGR.STEVE MCNAUGHTON.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: ON SATURDAY, 030594, AT ABOUT 0200 HOURS UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CTS T.M. ROBINSON WAS CALLED BY UPRR CORRIDOR MGR. D. SPRINGER FROM THE HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER. SPRINGER ADVISED THAT THE A UPRR TRAIN CRREW WORKING AT DONALDSONVILLE, LOUISIANA REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA. THE CAR WAS SET BACK OUT AT DONALDSONVILLE, BUT THE ODOR WAS NOT EFFECTING TRAIN OPERATIONS. SPRINGER ADVISED THAT HE HAD NOT CONTACTED ANY ONE ELSE, BUT WOULD MAKE ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATIONS. UPON ARRIVAL AT ABOUT 0301 HOURS, ROBINSON OBSERVED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND NO OTHER PERSONNEL WERE ABOUT. INSPECTION BY ROBINSON REVEALED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID AMMONIA WAS LEAKING FROM BENEATH THE PACKING GLAND RETAINER OF THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE. ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE TWO MACHINE SCREWS HOLDING THE RETAINER AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT ROBINSON HAD REMOVED SEAL "AMPRO" FERTILIZER 022797" FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING IN ORDER TO SECURE THE LEAKAGE. DUE TO SOME CONFUSION REGARDING THE FACT THAT AMPRO FERTILIZER HAD LOADED THE CAR, WHILE FIRST MISSISSIPPI WAS LISTED AS THE SHIPPER, THE CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION BY SPRINGER DID NOT RESULT IN A RESPONSE BY AMPRO OR FIRST MISSISSIPPI TO THE SCENE. ROBINSON DID TELEPHONE MR. STEVE MISTRETTA, MANAGER OF SECURITY & SAFETY FOR THE JOINT FACILITY OF AMPRO AND TRIAD CHEMICALS AT DONALDSONVILLE. MISTRETTA WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AND STATED THAT THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH LOADING PERSONNEL AT AMPRO. ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED AT THE SCENE BY MR. ROY SAVOY, C.F. IND. AND MR. DAVID WEBRE AND TWO OTHER TECHNICIANS REPRESENTING THE ASCENSION PARISH HAZ-MAT TEAM. ROBINSON WAS ALSO MET AT THE SCENE BY MR. TOM RICHARDS, UPRR MTO-AVONDALE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO DESTINATION AT ABOUT 0500 HOURS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS R. JONES WAS NOTIFIED OF LEAKING TANK CAR THAT HAD BEEN SET OUT AT UPRR YARD, KESLO CA. MO235. SAHM JONES RESPONDED, AND INSPECTING THE TANK CAR FOUND THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED, CAUSING MATERIAL RELEASE. SAHM REPLACED RUPTURED DISC WITH NEW BS&B 100# DISC. SAHM JONES NOTIFIED BOTH SHIPPER, AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT OF REPAIR.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D. A. LOW, DURING HIS COMPLIANCE CHECK OF TRAIN OGCY-8, SOUTH SIX TRACK, NOTED TANK CAR UTLX 110034, HAVING LIQUID COMING FROM UNLOADING CONNECTION BLIND FLANGE. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT 4-1/2 INCH ALLEN BOLTS AND NUTS WERE LOOSE ON BLIND FLANGE. SECURED BLIND FLANGE BOLTS AND NUTS WHICH STOPPED LEAK. JIM MALZZIO, CHEMTREC AND DAN MORRELL, NU-WEST INDUSTRIES WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS. D. A. LOW APPLIED SEAL; UP-C-54670 TO PROTECTIVE HOUSING.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS IN THE OGDEN YARD, INSPECTED EMPTY TANKCAR FLJX000009, LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS. NOTED SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK AT THE GAUGING ROD. REPAIR REQUIRED, TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT, ABOUT ONE HALF TURN. NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, SPOKE WITH MR. JIM LONG, HE INDICATED THAT THE SHIPPER WOULD BE INFORMED, HE ALSO ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 27331. MR. JOHN LYON MANAGER TO TRAIN OPERATIONS AT OGDEN, WAS NOTIFIED, AND THE CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY YARDMASTER AT 18TH STREET YARD ADVISING CAR ACFX 84682 WAS ENTRAINED IN KCS TRAIN AND WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. ON GROUND INSPECTION DEVELOPED THAT THERE WAS A CONTINOUS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. REMOVED INTACT SHIPPER SEAL "KRC 7611" FROM THE STUFFING BOX COVER AND FOUND THE TOP OPERATING ROD COULD BE TURNED 1/3 OF A TURN WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. ALSO NOTED THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE STUFFING BOX WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT. AFTER SECURING COVER APPLIED SEAL "UP X 140915". FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT AND THIS WAS ALSO SECURED. FURNISHED INFORMATION TO CHEMTREC, MR. TOM FLORES THEIR REPORT # 27343. ALSO ADVISED TRAFFIC MANAGER AT KOCH MR LOUIS DILLON OF THE ACTION TAKEN.

ON THURSDAY, 3/10/94, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER-CTS T. M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED THAT ACFX 85238, LOCATED AT ADDIS, LOUISIANA WAS EMITTING A VERY LOUD CONTINOUS VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY ON TOP OF THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED BY UPRR MOT BOB LENZER AND MEMBERS OF THE ADDIS VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT AND THE WEST BATON ROUGE HAZ-MAT TEAM UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF DEPUTY PHILL SMITH. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THIS CAR HAD BEEN WORKED ON, AT THE UPRR YARD AT ADDIS LOUISIANA ON 2/4/94 BY MR. CHARLES SMITH, A REPAIR TECHNICIAN FOR ACFX INDUSTRIES. MR. SMITH INSTALLED AN NEW DISC AT THAT TIME. THE CAR HAD REMAINED AT ADDIS IN BAD ORDER STATUS SINCE THAT TIME AWAITING A PART FOR THE BRAKE SYSTEM. THE RESIDUE MATERIAL IN THE CAR APPARENTLY HAD REESTABLISHED PRESSURE AND THE REGULATOR VALVES WERE NOT WORKING PROPERLY TO RELIEVE SAME CAUSING THE RECENTLY INSTALLED DISC TO FAIL. ROBINSON SPOKE WITH MR. DAVID JOINER, MANAGER PRODUCT SUPPLY FOR AIR LIQUIDE, MR. JOINER WAS ADVISED OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES OF THE INCIDENT AND AGREED WITH THE ASSESMENT OF ALL CONCERNED THAT THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO ALLOW THE CAR TO VENT THE REMAINING PRESSURE OFF. JOINER FURTHER ADVISED THAT HE WOULD CONTACT ACFX INDUSTRIES AND HAVE THE REGULATOR VALVES REPAIRED AS WELL AS REPLACEMENT OF THE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT LENZER HAD ALSO NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AS REQUIRED BY LAW.

REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY CAR FORMAN RICK MONGER AT 2100 HOURS ADVISING CAR ACFX 71819 WAS ENTRAINED IN TRAIN KCNLB-12 ON TRACK 303 AND WAS VENTING A CLOUD OF VAPOR ABOVE CAR. MR. STINE INSPECTED CAR AND WAS FOUND THERE WAS PRESSURE VENTING FROM BENEATH THE DISC RETAINER/ SPLASH DEFLECTOR. RELEASED THE SLIGHT INTERNAL PRESSURE AND DISMANTLED THE VENT ASSEMBLE NOTING THE "OSECO" 100 LB FRANGIBLE DISC APPEARED INTACT HOWEVER THE TEFLON GASKET WAS COMPRESSED POSSIBLY ALLOWING VAPOR TO ESCAPE. PLACED A NEW "OSECO" FRANGIBLE DISC IN PLACE AND SECURED FITTING WHICH CORRECTED THE LEAK. MR. SONNY ROMMELMAN AT "ELF" INDICATED THE MATERIAL IS GENERALLY PRESSURED OFF AND IT WAS POSSIBLE THAT CREWS UNLOADING THE CAR INADVERTENTLY FAILED TO RELEASE ALL OF THE PRESSURE FROM UNLOADING. MR. JIM LONG AT CHEMTREC WAS FURNISHED INFORMATION AT 2230 HOURS, REPORT #27392.

REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED MY MYO JIM COX ADVISING THAT CAR GATX 92862 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM A FITTING ON TOP WITH A SIX INCH WIDE STREAM OF LIQUID RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR. MR. STINE REMOVED INTACT SHIPPER SEAL "UP H 55089" FROM THE TOP LOADING LINES PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND NOTED A PENCIL SIZE STREAM OF ALCOHOL COMING FROM BETWEEN THE VALVE BASE AND THE CAR LIQUID LINE FLANGE. CONTACTED MR. A.D. MATY AAR CHIEF INSPECTOR WHO RESPONDED TO ASSIST. REMOVED INTACT SHIPPER SEAL "UP H 55074" FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE ALLOWING INTERNAL PRESSURE TO ESCAPE WHICH STOPPED THE PERCOLATION OF THE LIQUID. ONE OF FOUR ATTACHMENT STUDS WAS LOOSE IN THE NOZZLE FLANGE PLATE. REMOVED THE 3' JAMESBURY VALVE AND NOTED THE "STUDS" APPEARED TO BE ALL THREAD ROD INSTEAD OF STANDARD STUDS. TAP HOLE IN FLANGE WAS STRIPPED SO USED "PERMATEX LOCKTITE" THREAD RESTORING COMPOUND, BEING APPLIED TO THE TAPPED HOLE THEN RE-APPLIED THE STUD. ALLOWED 30 MINUTES CURE TIME THEN APPLIED THE LIQUID VALVE. ALSO NOTED THE FITTED MANWAY GASKET WAS SPLIT; SOME SILICONE SEALANT HAD BEEN APPLIED TO THE GAP IN THE GASKET; THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LEAKAGE AT THIS LOCATION. CAR WAS CHECKED AT 2100 HOURS WITH NO EVIDENCE OF ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE AND IT WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION. SHIPPER CONTACT MR. GREG HOUER WAS FURNISHED INFORMATION AND INDICATED THEY DO NOT USE THESE VALVES DURING LOADING JUST CHECK FOR THEM TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED AND PLUGS IN PLACE. CAR HAD BEEN LOADED WITH A PRODUCT TEMPERATURE OF 70 DEGREES WITH OUTAGE TWO INCHES BELOW THE 2 PERCENT BAR. WILL HAVE THE VALVE CHECKED WHEN THE CAR RETURNS EMPTY. MR. MARVIN GLOTZBACH, KDHE WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON 031494 AT APPROXIMATELY 8AM REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE LAREDO TRUCK LINES MANAGER, ROBERT GAONZALES. HE REPORTED THE ABOVE TRAILER WAS LEAKING A GREEN/BROWN LIQUID FROM THE FLOOR. IT SPILLED ON THE FLATCAR AND TRAILER BUT, HAD NOT REACHED THE GROUND. REEDER TRAVELLED TO LAREDO AND INSPECTED THE SCENE. REEDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER LISTED ON THE WAYBILL AND WAS REFERRED TO FUJI HUNT, THE COMPANY THAT LOADED THE TRAILER. AFTER A LENGTHY DISCUSSION, FUJI WAS UNABLE TO ACCURATELY DETERMINE WHAT WAS IN THE TRAILER. USING PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT REEDER ENTERED THE TRAILER DETERMINED THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED. HE ALSO LEARNED THAT A PALLET HAD SHIFTED AND CRUSHED A BOX CONTAINING PLASTIC BOTTLES OF PRODUCT. AGAIN FUJI WAS CONTACTED AND GIVEN THE PRODUCT NAME, HOWEVER, THEY COULD NOT POSITIVELY IDENTIFY THE MATERIAL WITHOUT THE CATALOG NUMBER. REEDER AGAIN ENTERED THE TRAILER TO OBTAIN THE CATALOG NUMBER. ONCE THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED, INSTRUCTIONS WERE GIVEN ON HOW TO NEUTRALIZE THE MATERIAL. SINCE THE BOTTLES WERE NOW EMPTY AND NO PRODUCT WAS LEAKING, THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE WHERE IT WAS REARRANGED BEFORE DELIVERY TO FINAL DESTINATION. SEAL FUJI-HUNT 03182 WAS REMOVED BY REEDER. THE TRAILER WAS NOT RESEALED AT THE REQUEST OF FUJI HUNT.

VAPOR LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED BY AN FRA INSPECTOR, ANTHONY SCHNEIDER, ON 03-11-94 AT 11:00 A.M. DURING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTION.  HE DETERMINED THE CAUSE TO BE INSECURE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND THE INCREASE IN AMBIENT TEMPERATURE THAT DAY.  A WITCO REPRESENTATIVE AND MYSELF EXAMINED THE MANWAY COVERS AND GASKETS AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO LOOSE MANWAY BOLTS THAT WERE NOT TIGHT ENOUGH TO SECURE THE CARS FOR TRANSPORATION.  THE CARS WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MARCH 11, 1994  TRUCK ACCIDENT  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM ON 3/10/94, TRANSPORATION ASSISTANT RUSS NICKELL AND I (BILL THOMPSON) WERE CONTACTED BY THE STURGEON & SON, INC.  DRIVER LISTED BELOW WHO REPORTED THAT, APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES EARLIER, AT 9:15 AM, HE HAD OVERTURNED HIS STURGEON & SON, INC. TRACTOR/TRAILER DESTINED FOR CAMERON-YAKIMA, INC. IN YAKIMA, WASHINGTON WHILE NORTHBOUND ON HWY 97 ON THE NORTH SIDE OF KLAMATH FALLS, OREGON.  HE WAS TRANSPORTING 103 DRUMS AND 2 VESSELS CONTAINING RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE, NON-RCRA HAZARDOUS (CALIFORNIA HAZARDOUS ONLY) AND NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE.  WEST ADVISED US THAT HE MUST HAVE BLACKED-OUT MOMENTARILY BECAUSE THE NEXT THING HE KNEW, HE WAS OVER AN EMBANKMENT ABOUT 30' - 40 ' FROM THE ROADWAY AND THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS ON ITS SIDE.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER CAME TO REST ON OREGON DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORATION PROPERTY 9' FROM THE FENCE LINE OF THE NEAREST PROPERTY OWNER AND 270' SOUTH OF MILE MARKER 273 ON THE WEST SIDE OF HWY 97.  THE OREGON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE OREGON HIGHWAY PATROL, TELEPHONE (503) 883-5711, WAS ON THE SCENE AND I SPOKE TO OFFICER PEPCO COURTNEY.  RUSS NICKELL SUGGESTED AND OFFICER COURTNEY AGREED THAT WE SHOULD SEND PROFILE SHEETS OF THE VAN'S CONTENTS TO ASSIST COURTNEY IN DETERMINING THE CONTENTS.  OFFICER COURTNEY ADVISED US THAT THEY HAD CLOSED HWY 97 AND EVACUATED 2 OR 3 RESIDENCES AS A PRECAUTION.  WE ADVISED OFFICER COURTNEY THE CONTENTS IN THE TRAILER WERE NON THREATENING TO THE RESIDENCES AND THE HIGHWAY TRAVELLERS, HOWEVER, HE STATE FOR LIABILITY CONCERNS THEY TOOK THIS ACTION UNTIL THEY WERE CONVINCED IT WAS SAFE.  THE HIGHWAY WAS REOPENED AND THE RESIDENTS RETURNED TO THEIR HOMES IN APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS.  NICKELL ADVISED OFFICER COURTNEY DRUMS IN THE TRAILER CONTAINED SPENT ACTIVATED CARBON FROM VARIOUS GENERATORS.  WEST RESPONDED TO MERLE WEST MEDICAL SERVICE IN KLAMATH FALLS WHERE HE WAS EXAMINED BY DR. HENSEN  AND WAS NIDA DRUG TESTED.  DR.  HANSEN SPOKE TO ME LATER BY TELEPHONE AND SAID THAT WEST SUSTAINED NO INJURIES AND WAS BEING RELEASED.  DR. HANSEN SAID HE BELIEVED WEST'S BLACK-OUT WAS CAUSED BY "COUGH SYNCOPE" WHICH CAUSES THE VICTIM TO BLACK-OUT WHEN COUGHING VIOLENTLY.  DR HANSEN SAID THAT WEST ALMOST PASSED OUT WHILE COUGHING IN HIS PRESENCE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE HAZARDOUS WASTE RESPONSE TEAM DETERMINED ONE DRUM CONTAINING SPENT CARBON HAD A SMALL PINHOLE ON THE BOTTOM WHICH BEGAN TO SEEP MINUTELY WHEN PLACED IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION.  THE PINHOLE WAS NOTICED IMMEDIATELY AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK BEFORE THE MATERIAL COULD SEEP INTO THE TRAILER.  THIS DRUM, WHOSE GENERATOR IS SANTA FE PACIFIC PIPELINES, INC. 888 SOUTH FIGUEROA ST. LOS ANGELES, CA, WAS MANIFESTED HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, N.O.S. (D018) 9 NA 3077 PG 111.  FOUR OTHER DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE HOLES PUNCHED INTO THEIR LIDS WITH 3 OF THEM IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION. THEY WERE CAREFULLY PLACED IN OVERPACKS FOR TRANSPORATION WITH NO SPILLAGE.  THE FOURTH DRUM WAS LEANING AT AN ANGLE WITH ABOUT A 3"
SHIPPER ISSUED TWO DELIVERES TO THIS ONE LOCATION.  THE SECOND DELIVERY ON THE SAME DATE RESULTED IN AN OVERFILLED.

PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP BY TIM MICKENS AND PLACED IN OUR AREA TO BE INSPECTED.  THE PACKAGE AND DETERMINED THAT THE CAPS WERE LOOSE IN TWO OF THE FOUR-1 GALLON BOTTLES.  THERE WAS VERY LITTLE LEAKAGE.  1 OZ.  PER GALLON.  I DIDN'T WRITE A DIR:  IT WAS REBOXED AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE. RELABEL AND CORRECTLY ACCORDING TO DOT REGULATIONS.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column168: PSC CLERK KATHY PIRRWITZ WAS CALLED TO PD10 WHERE SHE FOUND A WET BOX IN THE FEEDER.  SHE TOOK IT TO THE QD1 REWRAP AREA WHERE UPON INSPECTION SHE FOUND THE CAP LOOSE.  IT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CONTAINER REPACKED AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE,  THE ORIGINAL CARTON WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM, ACCORDING TO UPS PROCEDURES.  THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN STOPPED IN THE FEEDER AND THE AREA CLEARED WHEN PSC CLERK KATHY PIRRWITZ ARRIVED TO PD10, WEARING THE PPE ITEMS.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN PRIMARY SORT.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE AS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGE CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: AN UNLOADER UNLOADED A PACKAGE, I WAS DEMONSTRATING PROPER HAND TO SURFACE METHODS. I FELT THAT THE BOTTOM OF IT WAS WET. I LOOKED FOR HAZ MAT TAG OR LABEL, NONE THERE. I SHUT DOWN ENTIRE PRIMARY OPERATION AND CAUTIONED EMPLOYEES TO CLEAR AREA. I CALLED FOR HELP FROM OTHER IZ HR. RESPONDER, NATE TREECE. WE NOTICED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS BY THE SMELL. I DONNED PPE GRABBED A HAZ MAT TUB, PLACED PACKAGE IN TUB AND REMOVED IT FROM THE BUILDING. I RETURNED TO THE BELT, SPILL SITE, USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE IT, SOLUSORB TO ABSORB IT AND REMOVED THAT FROM BUILDING. I REFERRED TO HAZ RESPONSE BOOKLET FOR FURTHER CLEAN UP. CALLED BOB STEMPLE FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. DOUBLE CHECKED PH LEVEL, HAZ MAT BAGS WERE USED AND REMAINS WERE DISPOSED OF.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: UNITED AIRLINES FLIGHT 1281/13 MAR, A REGULARLY SCHEDULED PASSENGER FLIGHT FROM PORTLAND OREGON TO LOS ANGELES, CA. HAD TO DRIVE AND MAKE AN UNSCHEDULED LANDING IN SACRAMENTO, CA.  DUE TO THE SMELL OF GASOLINE WERE FOUND IN A BOX IN AN OVERHEAD BIN.  THE CHAIN SAWS BELONGED TO PASSENGER SILVESTRE MORENO AND WERE BROUGHT ABOARD BY THE PASSENGER IN PDX.  THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ITEM AND WAS NOT PROPERLY PACKED, MARKED, LABELLED OR DECLARED TO UNITED AIRLINES.  THE FAA REP. JEANNETTE BEAN 415-876-2853 WAS NOTIFIED AT 0845 ON 03/13/94.  THEY REQUESTED WE HOLD THE ITEM FOR THEIR INSPECTION.

column168: S/A, BALLANCE WAS ADVISED THAT LARGE AMOUNTS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE HAD BEEN SPILLED ON AN INDUSTRY SPUR. HE WAS ALSO ADVISED TO THE CONTACT JERRY AT PACIFEX REGARDING THE SPILLED PRODUCT. AFTER CONTACTING PACIFEX, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT HAD COME FROM ONE OF TWO CARS, GTAX-20239 OR BN 457739. BN 457739 WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD ORDER. CAR GTAX 20239 WAS FOUND TO HAVE A BROKEN LOCKING MECHANISM WHICH ALLOWED THE OUTLET PLATE TO SLIDE OPEN ON THE NUMBER ONE COMPARTMENT. OHM WAS REQUESTED TO ASSIST IN THE SPILLED PRODUCT. TWO VACUUM TRUCKS WERE REQUESTED TO PICK-UP THE PRODUCT FROM BETWEEN THE MAINLINE AT FRENCH CAMP ROAD, BETWEEN THE TRACKS AT PACIFEX AND SMALL AMOUNTS THAT WERE FOUND AT THE ENTRANCE TO THE SHARPE ARMY DEPOT. THE PRODUCT WAS STORED AT PACIFEX AND LATER REMOVED BY A LOCAL NURSERY.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MGR, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY BOB SCHUT, SUPV YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA., THAT TANK CAR GATX 36040 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT A RATE OF 3.4 DROPS PER MINUTE. MECHANICAL DEPT. FORCES ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TO CURTAIL THE LEAK, HOWEVER, THEY NOTED NO SIGNIFICANT CHANGE IN THE DRIP RATE. A ONE GALLON PAIL WAS ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET TO PREVENT LOSS OF ADDITIONAL LIQUIDS. THE YARD TRACK WAS BLUE FLAGGED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MRG COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACITLITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE TOP VALVE COVER/HANDLE DID NOT HAVE SEAL PROTECTION. UPON INVERTING THE COVER/HANDLE AND PLACING IT ON THE OPERATING ROD, THE HANDLE WAS TURNED ONE FULL ROTATION TO PROPERLY SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET, THUS CURTAILING THE LEAK. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDINO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SVCS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH ON I-495 AROUND WASHINGTON, DC, TSMT DRIVER WAS ALERTED OVER CB RADIO BY A FOLLOWING TRUCK THAT MATERIAL WAS BEING RELEASED FROM REAR OF TRAILER. TSMT DRIVER THEN PULLED TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT SEVERAL 5 GALLON METAL CANS OF WASTE, PAINT RELATED MATERIAL WERE LEAKING. THE TSMT DRIVER PLACED PLASTIC ON THE GROUND TO CATCH DRIPPING MATERIAL. THE MONTGOMERY COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM ARRIVED ON THE SCENE (UNKNOWN WHO NOTIFIED) AND BEGAN THEIR ASSESSMENT OF THE SITUATION. THE NOTIFICATION PROCESS WAS STARTED DUE TO THE FACT IT WAS UNKNOWN OF AN RQ HAD BEEN REACHED. THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT WAS NOTIFIED (JIM HAUSNER) AT 14:12 CST FOLLOWED BY NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 14:20 CST, REPORT NO. 229343. THE NRC CONTACTED EPA REGION III. AT THE REQUEST OF THE MONTGOMERY COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM, A REMEDIATION FIRM, REMAC USA, INC., WAS CONTACTED TO DO CLEAN-UP. REMAC DISCOVERED 41, 5 GALLON CANS LEAKING OR DAMAGED TO THE POINT THAT THEY REQUIRED OVERPACKING. THE LEAKAGE WAS CAUSED BY POOR QUALITY CONTAINERS AND IMPROPER  PREPARATION BY THE SHIPPER FOR TRANSPORTATION. IN ADDITION, THE LOAD WAS IMPROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED BY THE DRIVER. THE METAL CANS WERE STACKED 3 HIGH WITH APPROXIMATELY 31 TO A PALLET. THE CANS WERE SHRINK WRAPPED TOGETHER AND TAPED. AS THE TRUCK TRAVELED DOWN THE ROAD, THE SHRINK WRAPPING FAILED ALLOWING THE CANS TO ROLL FREE. SOME OF THE CANS WERE CRUSHED WHILE OTHERS HAD LOOSE FITTING CLOSURES WHICH ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL. IT IS MY OPINION THAT SHRINK WRAPPING IS NOT AND EFFECTIVE MEANS OF SECURING CARGO THAT HAS ANY WEIGHT TO IT. IF SHRINK WRAPPING IS USED, ADDITIONAL BLOCKING AND BRACING SUCH AS EMPTY PALLETS STOOD ON END AND HELP IN PLACE WITH LOAD LOCKS COULD BE UTILIZED. UPON COMPLETION OF REMAC'S WORK, THE TRUCK WAS ALLOWED TO PROCEED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.

I, MICHAEL FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND DIANE FIGUEROA, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN RESPONDED TO THE HAZ-MAT SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, WE OBSERVED A FIBREBOARD BOX SETTING ON A TABLE.  DIANE DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTIAGE REPIRATOR AND BUTYL GLOVES TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSIDE THE FIRBREBOARD BOX WERE TWO 500 ML CAPACITY, PLASTIC RECEPTICLES WERE MARKED "NITRIC ACID".  THE OUTER FIRBEBOARD BOX WAS MARKED "CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORM-D". I KAREN NICHLOS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC.  145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT ON 03-22-94 AT APPROXIMATELY 0153 HRS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BEFORE IT WAS UNLOADED FROM AIRCRAFT N814AX OF FLIGHT 0397, ORD-ILN.  THE GROUND CREW NOTICED AN ODOR THEN A PUDDLE OF LIQUID ON THE TOPSIDE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT DURING THE OFFLOAD.  ALL 7 EMPLOYEES EVACUATED THEMSELVES FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  OUR HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM RESPONDED AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL, DONNED IN FIRE FIGHTER BUNKER GEAR AND SELF-CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS.  WE FOUND A 5-GALLON STEEL DRUM (DOT 37C80) IN ONE OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICES WHICH WAS LEAKING THE MATERIAL IN QUESTION.  ACCORDING TO THE WARNING LABEL ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM, THE PRODUCT WAS MASTERKURE, A COMPOUND CURING GROUT.  OUR HAZ MAT SPILL TEAM PLACED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD IT AT THE SAME LOCATION IN OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY STORAGE AREA PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  THE SHIPMENT HAD NO DOT HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT.  NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES IN THE AREA SUFFERED ILL EFFECTS FROM THEIR EXPOSURE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS INVESTGATED FURTHER AND WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE DRUM.  THERE IS A DENT IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM AND THE LEAK SEEMS TO BE COMING FROM THE SEAM.  THE WARNING LABEL ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS FLAMMABLE.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER AND ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.
